<p><a href="https://nexus.od.nih.gov/all/2020/04/17/cyber-safety-covid-19/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">NIH: Cyber Safety &amp; COVID-19</span></a><br /><span style="font-weight: 400;">The current outbreak of the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) has introduced new cybersecurity risks both at NIH and across the globe. As targeted phishing attacks prey on our desire to access trustworthy information and many of us make a shift toward remote work, we all need to be vigilant and take accountability for cyber safety.</span></p>
<p><a href="https://www.gatesnotes.com/Health/Pandemic-Innovation?WT.mc_id=20200423060000_Pandemic-Innovation_MED-media_&amp;amp;WT.tsrc=MEDmedia"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The First Modern Pandemic: The scientific advances we need to stop COVID-19</span></a><br /><span style="font-weight: 400;">It&rsquo;s an especially challenging time to be an optimist right now. As </span><a href="https://go.communications.gatesfoundation.org/e/701613/vation-GFG-TOP--WT-tsrc-GFGTOP/bv4pj/119615087?h=z3CIPWr2fUyuhaf4Irl7Bnwg37wmaef6axRSQSOpj0M"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Bill Gates says in a thoughtful and comprehensive essay on COVID-19</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> published this week, &ldquo;It is impossible to overstate the pain people are feeling now and will continue to feel for years to come.&rdquo; His analysis of what he calls the first modern pandemic concludes that global innovation is the key to limiting the damage. Not only in science and technology, but also in leadership and policy&mdash;especially when it comes to discussions around lifting economic and social restrictions.&nbsp;</span></p>
